4.68/5  rDev +4.7%look: 4.5 | smell: 4.5 | taste: 4.75 | feel: 4.75 |  overall: 4.75Prairie's Barrel Aged Bomb!, whiskey barrel aged stout, with coffee, cocoa nibs, vanilla beans, and chillies. 11.2% ABV.
A: About half a finger of cocoa cereal colored head. Black in the glass. Very dark brown in the dimple; with a reddish edge. Solid sheeting; no lacing. Very faint inkiness.
S: Rich chocolate cake on opening the bottle. Light coffee. Just a touch of char. Dark toffee, oak, and leather in the back. Very much like a less sweet Birthday Bomb!
T/MF: Much more dark toffee and oak and... Ooh. Lost focus on that transition. A touch of char, as well, but then a nice hit of caramel steps up, with an almost floral sweetness. Followed immediately by a rich chocolate, just shy of bittersweet. A touch of spice comes through on further sips. Kind of between cinnamon and nutmeg. Slight tobacco note. Body is soft and smooth. Just the right amount of carbonation (that is to say, almost none, but not flat, with just a hint of tingle).
Overall, not quite as good as the Birthday Bomb!, but a very nice beer for slow, calm, contemplative drinking.
Poured from a 12 oz. bottle, into a Belgian tulip glass. 1,121 charactersTruePerception, Jan 23, 2017
4.7/5  rDev +5.1%look: 4.75 | smell: 4.75 | taste: 4.75 | feel: 4.25 |  overall: 4.75Poured from single-serve bottle....
Initially flat and oily pour, but the head "pops" at the last minute to a two-finger tan.  This may be the blackest most-opaque beer I've ever sampled.  Impressive to say the least.
Aromas of coffee, cocoa, and vanilla notes followed by the bourbon notes.  The alcohol is noticeable on the nose, but not offputting.  Very "stout" aroma and lots of it.  
The flavors are complex and play well with each other.  Very malty sweet up front, but ample background bitter coffee and chocolate flavors balance this perfectly.  Clean solvent alcohol "bite" but not burn.  The chilis are not present as an aroma, or a true flavor, but in addition to the boozy bite on the tongue, there is the unmistakable chili heat on the back of the throat.  I'm not completely sold that the barrel aging is a big "add" here because....
As is often the case, this barrel aged offering seems a little "thin" for the style.  It also lacks a bit on the carbonation side.
Overall, this is a truly unique, well-balanced, and outstanding offering that is at once experimental while also remaining pretty faithful to the style. 1,137 charactersMindcrime1000, Jan 22, 2017
