4.35/5  rDev -2.7%look: 4.25 | smell: 4.75 | taste: 4.25 | feel: 4 |  overall: 4.2512 fl oz bottle sealed with pressure cap.
poured into Speigelau Bourbon County snifter.
Appearance: dark black body with medium brown head that pours two fingers tall and quickly drops down to thick cap. Thick booze legs on the glass after each sip. About halfway through drinking the beer only a thin ring of head remains.
Smell: Lots of wet oak barrel character and top shelf bourbon. This smells very chocolatey and there is a hint of vanilla as well. Hint of lightly roasty coffee.  Hint of earthy and smokey peppers. Barrel and adjuncts are all present in the nose.  I really like the intense aroma of the whiskey in this beer, but this definitely trumps the adjuncts of prairie bomb. 
Taste: Bakers cocoa, lots of wet oak, and top shelf bourbon are the biggest flavors in this beer. Hints of smoke and charred oak barrel; vanilla, stale coffee, caramel, rootbeer, and cola are present in small proportions. Finishes with a lightly earthy and smokey bitterness from the peppers and a splash of vanilla beans.   
Mouthfeel: medium bodied beer with low carbonation. This seems substantially thinner than prairie bomb, but still feels slightly oily. Not a hint of booze from this beer.
Overall: Really awesome barrel notes in this beer, but the adjuncts seem to be substantially faded when comparing the aroma to the flavor profile of this beer. I would have liked to taste more of the peppers and get that heat from them, but barrel aging must take the sting of the peppers away. 1,488 characters4DAloveofSTOUT, Dec 29, 2016
