4.49/5  rDev +0.4%look: 4.25 | smell: 4.5 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 4.5 |  overall: 4.5BMMillsy, Dec 17, 2016
4.7/5  rDev +5.1%look: 4.25 | smell: 4.75 | taste: 4.75 | feel: 4.5 |  overall: 4.75Picked up a bottle today at Beermongers for $8.20 a pop.  Definitely worth the price of admission for this delicious beer.
The beer pours a thick blackish brown color, looking more like motor oil than a well crafted RIS.  Head retention is pretty good, and lacing is light and sticky.  This beer has the look of one that has seen some considerable barrel aging.  The nose is the first give away that this is going to be something special.  There's a huge aroma of coffee, green chili's, Mexican chocolate, nestles quick, vanilla and dark chocolate.  There's a hint of coconut as well, if that isn't sufficient.  The flavor profile replicates the nose pretty closely in this rich, sweet, decadent impy stout, with the green chili's imparting just enough spice and heat to lightly counter the sweetness in this rich beer.  There's some noticeable whiskey on the nose and on the palate, but it's really blended in pretty nicely with the other components in this beer.  Mouthfeel is soft and very full, and the finish just goes on and on.  Alcohol is well integrated into the flavor profile, with no sense of heat or heaviness on the palate.  You can certainly tell that the abv. is up there a bit, but even so, this is a pretty easy beer to take. 
Another excellent beer from Prairie.  These bomb and noir barrel aged beers are really where this brewery seems to shine.  Another impressive effort from the folks at Prairie. 1,422 charactersJohn_M, Dec 17, 2016
4.34/5  rDev -2.9%look: 4 | smell: 4.25 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 4.25 |  overall: 4.2512oz bottle purchased from Bedford, OH Lizardville for $12 American dollars. Julian dated 11/18/2016.
Vigorous pour into snifter yields a 2 finger tan head which quickly dissipates to a thin collar. No lacing but legs as the tasting proceeds. 
There was a huge pepper aroma as the cap was popped and as the brew was swirled in the vessel the pepper and spice was mellowed by a nice chocolate, roasted malt and caramel fragrance.  The barrel and whiskey were faintly present.
Now here is where this brew excels: pepper, spice co-mingle with a nice whiskey, barrel, caramel and char.  The heat is a bit too mellowed for my taste but does does blend nicely.
Full body, slick and sticky, peppered.
A nice RIS but I was hoping for a bit more whisky and pepper to balance the base. 780 charactersCaptCleveland, Dec 17, 2016
