4.5/5  rDev +0.7%look: 4.5 | smell: 4.5 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 4.5 |  overall: 4.5HopsForBrains, Jun 02, 2016
4.43/5  rDev -0.9%look: 3.75 | smell: 4.5 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 4.25 |  overall: 4.5I picked up a bottle of Prairie;s Barrel Aged Bomb! for $11.39 at The Lager Mill.  I've been wanting to try this ever since I first had Bomb!, so lets see how it goes.  2016 Vintage.  Poured from a brown 12oz bottle into a snifter.
A-  The label looks good, it's weird and eye catching.  It poured a nice dark black color that took on just a slight bit of a brown hue when held to the light with just a thin ring worth of darker tan head that eventually faded away to nothing and it didn't really leave any lacing behind.  This is a pretty nice looking beer, but I wish the head and lacing were better.  
S=  The aroma starts off with a lower amount of high sweetness with the bourbon barrels being the first to show up and they impart a nice noticeable bourbon barrel aroma with some wood and bourbon notes coming through and it's followed by a big chocolate aroma with some cocoa and it makes for a chocolate syrup like aroma.  Up next comes the spices which impart a mixture of the typical bomb spices showing up with just a little bit of a noticeable chili pepper like aroma with a little more dark roasted malts and sweet malts showing up towards the end.  This beer has a very good aroma, it's just what I would expect from a barrel aged version of Bomb.  
T-  The taste seems to be very similar to the aroma and it starts off with a lower amount of high sweetness with the bourbon barrels still being the first to show up and it's a good amount lighter than it was in the aroma, but it imparts all the same aspects and it's followed by some vanilla.  Up next comes the chocolate which imparts those same big chocolate syrup aspects that it did in the aroma and it's followed by the spices which impart the same aspects that they did in the aroma, but this time they are just a little lighter.  Towards the end comes a little bit of noticeable alcohol with a slight bit of that chili pepper coming through and on the finish there's hardly any bitterness with some sweetness taking it's place and it had a little bit of a lingering burn from the alcohol and chili and in the aftertaste there's some big chocolate syrup flavors with some spices and bourbon barrel flavors showing up.  This is a very good tasting beer, all the different aspect work very well together.  
M-  Pretty smooth, creamy, pretty velvety, a little warming,  on the lighter side of being full bodied with a slightly higher amount of medium carbonation.  The mouthfeel is very nice and it works well with this beer.
Overall I thought this was a very good beer and a very good example of the style, it had all those great flavors that bomb has and the addition of bourbon barrel really takes this beer to the next level and it makes for lots of complexity.  This beer has nice drinkability, one is the perfect amount for me.  What I like the most about this beer is how well all the different aspects worked together, it was very nice.  What I like the least about this beer is the appearance, I wish it had better head, retention and lacing.  I would for sure buy this beer again if I see it again and I would recommend it to anyone who likes big and complex barrel aged beers.  All in all I was very happy with this beer and I was impressed, sometimes beers can get to complex and the flavors start to clash, but that wasn't the case with this beer and I thought it was executed  very well.  It;s now my new favorite beer from Prairie and it's one of the better barrel aged Stouts I've had.  Great job guys, this is a really tasty and complex beer, keep up the hard work. 3,554 charactersStoutHunter, Jun 01, 2016
