4.56/5  rDev +2%look: 4.25 | smell: 5 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 4 |  overall: 4.5Drank from a 12Fl. Oz. bottle purchased at Quickie Pickie, Austin, TX
010716
Served in a snifter
Review #1150
Prairie Artisan Ales always have some incredible graphics on their bottles and this one might just be their most insane looking label to date. With an aggressive pour, a barely there, khaki colored film topped the thick, oily and nearly still, absolute pitch black liquid. The head morphed into a bubbly collar. Droplets of lacing trickled down the glass.
The aroma was outstanding. Super rich and fragrant. Freshly brewed coffee and chocolate fudge notes dominated. Perhaps some chocolate syrup as well. Sweet but not cloying. Loads of smooth bourbon. Vanilla also came through strong. Intense coconut notes. This reminded me a lot of Bourbon County Brand Coffee Stout.
The flavor profile was terrific but not quite as smooth or as intense as the aroma. Roasted malts were noticeable on the front end. Bit of chocolate fudge. Espresso came through in the center. Good dose of vanilla. More roast and char on the back end. Some whiskey. Very subtle spice notes appeared in the finish. I probably would not peg this for chillies though. There was a good amount of alcohol heat and a subtle, lingering bitterness as well.
The mouthfeel was rich and creamy but a bit undercarbonated. Fuller bodied for the style. The liquid contained a very fine and mellow effervescence. After each sip, the beer left a sticky film on my lips.
Barrel Aged Bomb! is a big and flavorful yet smooth and rounded imperial stout that demonstrates a subtle yet notable use of whiskey barrels. This beer is definitely more interesting and complex than regular BOMB! 1,654 charactersDamian, Mar 05, 2016
