4.69/5  rDev +4.9%look: 3.75 | smell: 4.75 | taste: 4.75 | feel: 4.75 |  overall: 4.75Right off the bat... 11.2% vs 14%... I don't think this actually Prairie Bomb thrown in barrels. And from the initial pour, with its dark brown color, It seems very likely now. 
Dark, dark brown in color, Pretty much black. No head to speak of. Some alcohol legs coming down. Looks OK. 
The smell is off the charts, however. It smells like a kahlua coffee and vanilla ice cream. Or like a spiked Affogatto (espresso shot with ice cream). The barrel is bringing large amounts of vanilla, coconut, vanilla and oak to the table. 
TONS of vanilla on the flavor. As if there were not enough vanilla in regular bomb. The vanilla bean is lingering and lingering. That kahlua coffee flavor backs it up and it goes down silky smooth and sweet. Nothing overpowering, just awesome. 
I am coming to the conclusion that they made a lighter version of the beer sans the adjuncts. Then aged it whiskey barrels, then added the coffee beans, the vanilla, etc. into the barrels with it for the last month or so or perhaps just into a bright tank all together; because the vanilla and coffee are shining through really nicely. 
Nearly flawless, similar in character to the recent Vanilla Noir. I am just missing some complexity. Some smoke, earthiness, tobacco, etc. would take this beer into the stratosphere (thank you, leo). Prairie seems to have their spice additions dialed down now. Lets see them make a beer like Parabola and add these spices for boost. 
Regardless, awesome beer. 1,474 charactersraynmoon, Feb 13, 2016
